    <item>
      <title>Congratulations in Science 2022</title>
      <link>//localhost:1313/news/science2022/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 02 Oct 2022 21:49:20 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>//localhost:1313/news/science2022/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;During the aging process, the brain experiences a significant loss of hypocretin (Hcrt)/orexin neurons. The high excitability of aged hypocretin neurons, characterized by depolarization of the resting potential, along with the adaptive upregulation of prepro-Hcrt mRNA expression, leads to fragmented sleep during aging. The aged Hcrt neurons with high excitability express a reduced M-current mediated by KCNQ2/3 channels, and the decreased expression of KCNQ2 impairs the neuron’s repolarization capacity.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
